    <section class="education-section">
      <h2>Understanding Cylinder Calculations</h2>
      <div class="content-cards">
        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>What is a Cylinder?</h3>
          <p>A cylinder is a three-dimensional solid figure with two parallel congruent circular bases connected by a curved surface. Common real-world examples include pipes, cans, water tanks, and columns.</p>
          <p>To accurately calculate its properties, you need two fundamental measurements: the radius (or diameter) of its circular base, and its overall height (or length).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>The Volume Formula</h3>
          <p>The volume of a cylinder represents the amount of space enclosed within it. It is calculated by finding the area of the circular base and multiplying it by the height.</p>
          <div class="formula-box">V = π × r² × h</div>
          <p>Where <strong>V</strong> is volume, <strong>π</strong> (Pi) is approximately 3.14159, <strong>r</strong> is the radius, and <strong>h</strong> is the height.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>Surface Area Formulas</h3>
          <p>The surface area comes in two parts: Lateral (the curved side) and Total (curved side plus the two bases).</p>
          <div class="formula-box">Lateral Area = 2 × π × r × h</div>
          <div class="formula-box">Total Area = 2πrh + 2πr²</div>
          <p>These calculations are crucial when determining how much material is needed to construct a tank or how much paint is required to coat a pipe.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="education-section">
      <h2>Practical Applications</h2>
      <div class="content-cards">
        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>Water Tanks & Cisterns</h3>
          <p>Calculating the volume of a cylindrical water tank allows you to determine its holding capacity. By converting cubic feet or cubic meters into gallons or liters, you can accurately gauge water storage for agricultural, residential, or industrial use.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>Pipe Volume & Flow</h3>
          <p>For plumbers and engineers, knowing the internal volume of a pipe is essential. It dictates the fluid capacity of a plumbing system, which is critical for determining pump sizes, water pressure, and calculating necessary drain capacities.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="content-card">
          <h3>Packaging & Manufacturing</h3>
          <p>Manufacturers rely on these calculations to design cans and containers. Balancing the volume (capacity) against the total surface area (material cost) allows companies to optimize their packaging for efficiency and profitability.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">How do you calculate the volume of a cylinder?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">To calculate the volume of a cylinder, you multiply the area of its circular base by its height. The formula is V = π × r² × h, where 'r' is the radius of the base and 'h' is the height. Make sure both measurements are in the same unit before calculating.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">How do I find the volume of a cylinder if I only have the diameter?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">If you have the diameter, first divide it by 2 to get the radius. For example, a diameter of 10 inches means the radius is 5 inches. Then use the standard volume formula: V = π × (d/2)² × h.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">What are common units for cylinder volume?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">Volume is universally measured in cubic units, such as cubic inches (in³), cubic feet (ft³), cubic centimeters (cm³), or cubic meters (m³). For practical applications involving liquids, it is often converted directly to fluid capacities like US gallons or liters.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">How do I calculate the capacity of a cylindrical water tank?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">Measure the inside radius and inside height of the tank. Calculate the volume using V = π × r² × h in cubic feet or cubic meters, then convert the result to gallons or liters using a standard conversion factor (e.g., 1 cubic foot = 7.48052 US gallons).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">Does the formula change for a hollow cylinder or pipe?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">For a hollow cylinder (like a thick-walled pipe), you calculate the volume of the outer cylinder and subtract the volume of the inner empty space. However, if you only want to know the fluid carrying capacity, simply use the internal radius in the standard volume formula.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

